re, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mathilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":7,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":17,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilda was born in 1089, in Malton, Yorkshire, England. She had at least 5 sons with Sweyn FitzAlaric. She died in 1159, in her hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1089–1159":"1089–1159","1080–1130":"1080–1130","–Male":"Surnud","1114–Male":"1114–Surnud","1118–1159":"1118–1159","1120–1159":"1120–1159","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1122–1172":"1122–1172","1080":"1080","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1172":"1172","